<br>
In Japan, the cursing is usually accomplished by using a low politeness level....involving different verb endings and different pronouns for &quot;I, You, He&quot;.<br>
<br>
The stuff that's similar to English cursing is pretty tame stuff... &quot;@#%$ !  F*** !  Damn !&quot; are usually translated as &quot;Kuso !&quot; or the stronger &quot;Chi-kuso !&quot;  (= problem, bloody problem)<br>
<br>
and <br>
<br>
&quot;idiot&quot; is usually translated as &quot;baka&quot; (= idiot) or &quot;aho&quot; (= idiot, in osaka-flavored Japanese) or &quot;baka-yaro&quot; (= damned idiot, and is usually an invitation to start fistfighting).<br>
<br>
Japanese cursing in American style doesn't get much beyond that flavorless stuff.  Where Japanese really shows a flair (and English is sadly lacking) is the aforementioned selection of politeness.<br>
For example, here are 3 columns: English, polite japanese, and cursing-Japanese.<br>
<br>
I                        watakushi                   ORE or WASHI<br>
You (one guy)      anata  or kimi             omae or koitsu<br>
you (plural)         anatagata, kimi-tachi   omaera<br>
he                      kare                           aitsu<br>
<br>
and now some verbs....<br>
<br>
please buy it      katte kudasai              kainasai !<br>
do it please       shite kudasai               shinSAya !<br>
<br>
(basically, notice that the rude verbs are short, and often command-like.  Try to think of someone with a bad hangover, talking as little as possible.) <br>
